	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Investigate whether the ordered triple <math>
                     <latex>(\Vect{x},\Vect{y},\Vect{z})</latex>
                  </math> of vectors below determine an orientation of  <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
			         <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}=(3,0,0)</latex>
                  </math>,   <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{y}=(2,-1,1)</latex>
                  </math>, and   <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{z}=(-1,-1,1)</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
			         <para>
               <para.body>If they do, which orientation?</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <approach version="1">
			      <answer.exercise>
            <answer.exercise.block>
               <answer.exercise.block.body>
				              <para>
                     <para.body>The vectors lie in a plane through the origin. Therefore they do not represent an orientation of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
			            </answer.exercise.block.body>
            </answer.exercise.block>
         </answer.exercise>
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>The question here is whether the three vectors lie in a plane through the origin. For, in this case, they form a degenerate triple which does not represent an orientation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>. Only if they do not lie in a plane through the origin do they represent an orientation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </solution.hint>
			      <solution>
            <solution.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Observe that <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{z}=\Vect{y} - \Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math>. Therefore the vectors lie in a plane through the origin and, therefore, do not represent an orientation of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </solution.body>
         </solution>
		    </approach>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	  <exercise>
